segments.text: He helped his father in the paint shop at the time.
And also, there was a, he called it a livery stable here.
And Daddy said he loved horses.
And he said that the man who had the livery stable would hire Daddy to go out.
People who came to town wouldn't have transportation sometimes.
And so they'd rent a buggy, a horse and buggy.
Well, they'd hire Daddy to go along to see they didn't abuse the horse and buggy
And he said he'd just ride all over the country, you know, and had a good time.
Said he loved doing that.
And I think that's interesting to me that he did that.
Now, some of those things I've almost forgotten that Daddy, in the last years, I'd ask him about, you know.
He told about how they'd go by relay, you know, they'd take some horses to, like, to Normandy or somewhere and then change horses and go on.
And he told about that, too, in his lifetime.
They did that.
That was interesting.
And I rode in a Surrey with a fringe on top.
Yeah, oh yeah.
I was at a meeting recently, and I said, I rode in a Surrey with a fringe on the top, and my sister said, you did not?
And I said, well, I certainly did.
I said, the Swinecoats had one across the street from us on 29th Street.
She says, well, I was going to say, ever since you were born, we had a car.
I said, but these people have a...
But our cars were in our barns then.
We didn't have garages, you know.
Do you ever remember anything when you were, you know, little or anything, you know, father and uncle remember that was really a luxury or something that, you know, something uncommon?
Like, let's say, you know, back then, you know, like women, it was, you know, silk or something like that and garments, you know, trying to get at.
Something that you thought was really something that was a... That I thought was a luxury?
Yeah.
Yeah.
It was something I thought of the other day.
Several of us were talking about what we used to think were rich people, you know?
Oh, yeah.
And my husband said, well, the people that he thought were rich when he was a boy were those who ordered...
He worked in the grocery store, and those who ordered...
asparagus were the rich people.
Let me see.
We think about that.
We all were laughing about who we thought were rich.
He said nobody but rich people used to eat asparagus.
What was the more wealthier people in Bryan's College Station here, what was their type of work?
What was the difference in their?
What was their type of income?
Oh, I think most of them had property down there.
Or some of them were owners of stores.
And some of the doctors were well.
The doctors here, I always thought were well off.
They're famous and dressed well and had a lot of advantages.
Did you ever hear anybody say about, you know, when the first car they ever saw come through dry or something like that?
No.
Daddy owned the second car that was ever in dry.
Oh, really?
What kind was it?
But he owned it second-hand.
Uh-huh.
I believe it was an EMF.
An EMF?
I remember the EMF.
He kept several cars, and we wished he'd get rid of them, and now I wish we had them.
Yeah.
Oh, they were marvelous.
They sat way up high, and they had these little lanterns on them.
You know, he kept them in the garage things.
When he'd get a new car, he'd keep those old ones.
Daddy liked things.
He understood about things like that.
We talk him out of it, you know, now.
And he had a Flanders.
I don't know if you ever heard of a Flanders.
No, I sure haven't.
That was a Flanders Roadster.
Yeah.
It was cute.
I think it was sort of like a sports roadster, if I remember.
But I remember those two were some of the first cars that ever came to mind.
They were, I guess then they had gas pumps or something like that.
I don't remember where we, everybody, everybody mended their own tires.
Nobody, as far as I know, mended your tire for you.
And they have, Daddy always patched his own tires.
And that was real exciting.
And he could do anything.
And he didn't like, didn't mind us watching him.
You know, we'd stand around and he'd patch this tire and he'd put this glue on it, you know, and.
Then he'd blow it up and see if it worked, you know.
Oh, men could do anything, you know, then.
And they practically had to, you know, survive.
That was interesting, though.
I think.
And then they put it in water to see if air was coming out, you know.
Sure, yeah, just like we do nowadays with bicycle tires.
Those things just entertain kids, you know, to watch that.
And Mother had a washing machine that Daddy bought her one time, and that was the funniest thing you ever saw.
It had...
wooden pegs in it like the end of a broomstick.
And you turn it around and it was lots harder work than washing by hand.
And it didn't do any good anyway.
It was a wooden tub.
I remember that.
And then I remember too we had, everybody had a cow or two.
Everybody lived far enough apart.
Oh really?
You didn't live jam up against each other.
And so you had a lot and where we lived
We lived at the other end of Haswell.
I keep moving back to Haswell here.
And when I, later after we left this house, that house.
And we had two or three lots around there.
You know, big areas.
And Daddy loved to garden.
He worked in the office in the daytime at night.
He had a beautiful garden.
He'd plow by me and my wife.
Was it a flower garden or more of a vegetable garden?
Well, we had flowers in the yard.
Pear trees and plum trees.
Oh, I like pears.
And we had grapes, and we had blueberries, and Daddy grew lettuce and every kind of vegetable.
And then he grew peanuts and kept them in the barn, and the kids would go in there and get those peanuts out.
Did a lot of people have their own gardens like that?
Oh, everybody had their own garden.
Everybody.
So the grocery store just carried the main staple.
I guess so, uh-huh.
Everybody had their own garden.
You remember the prices of things as compared to now, way back then, that your father talked about?
No, I can't remember that too much.
Because I know, you know, I remember my dad telling, my grandpa telling us about the prices and stuff.
I don't have any idea what the price is.
It's really... And I know somebody was saying what the price of bread was in relationship and what the size of the loaf was.
Well, I can't even remember if the loaves were smaller or bigger.
Mm-hmm.
But I remember Daddy used to buy five loaves a day.
Five loaves a day.
I said, Daddy, it looks like that would have made you go broke.
But they must have been smaller than that.
Sure, they must have been pretty.
And they'd be hot.
We'd get them at that bakery.
Yeah, uh-huh.
They'd be hot.

Was Brian mainly just centered around this one big street, you know, or was it kind of a network type, you know, or streets, you know, like we've been studying the different kinds of settlements, you know, they have linear settlements that were along a basic mode of, you know, a major mode of travel, you know, such as a railroad or road.
Yeah, they were just main streets, but then there were always people scattered out between Brian and college, you know.
Did they ever have a city square or anything like that?
I don't think you're at all, Brian didn't have a city square unless the courthouse would have been counted one, and I don't think we ever, you know, we didn't have one.
Was the courthouse counted right at the center of the city, though?
No.
It wasn't?
See, downtown, usually the square is in the middle of the stores, and we always had the courthouse on this side.
That's interesting, isn't it?
Yeah, that is.
That really is.
You remember talking about different,
the different parts of Bryan as, you know, like upper Bryan, lower Bryan, stuff like that.
Was it ever termed like that?
What do you mean by that?
You know, like... Like the caste system or like the... Well, like, you know, I'm going into town or I'm going, you know, you're... Well, it was just all one town.
And, like, when we lived in this house, that was the main part of town.
On 29th Street.
On the west side was the main part of town.
Then it came east.
Because of the highway?
I don't know why.
Well, I know Highway 6.
I never have understood why, but it did.
Highway 6 came through, and that shot everything over towards Texas Avenue.
You've got me interested in this, and I ask my sister a lot of questions.
So today I said, let's go by and see where that house was because I want to be sure what the address is.
And she says, all right, and I'll show you the house we lived in before.
You were born, and I said, you mean that's still standing?
I said, I didn't even know it.
We went by there, and it is beautiful.
The people who have bought it have kept it up, and it's just perfect.
That house is just gorgeous.
It's way over on the west side of town, and they've got the yard beautiful, and they still have that gingerbread on it that's in the picture, you know what I mean?
I don't have a picture of it, but anyway.
Isn't that wonderful that somebody's kept a house like that?
Yeah, that's... And she said, I'm going to go over there and ask them to let me see it.
Because I said, the lady we bought this house from moved to California.
She came back and we told her to come over and see us.
And so she says, oh, she's so glad to get to come back and see us.
Well, how big is your family?
How many brothers and sisters?
There were five.
Five of you all?
Five children.
Two of them are dead.
My two brothers are dead.
They died when we were like, since 19...
Sixty-nine, one brother in 1973.
And you and your sister?
Three sisters.
My two sisters live here.
They both live here in Bryan?
Uh-huh.
What do they do?
Montgomery works for the federal government, and Ms. Hudson lost her husband about two years ago, and she travels.
She's going to Europe next summer, and see some of Northern Europe.
Last summer they went to Japan and several places she'd been to, but she liked this man that takes them, and his wife.
They're just wonderful, pure guys.
And then she went to the Middle East with them one time.
And before then, she and her husband had an airstream, and they just traveled to Mexico and Canada with that group.
Do you ever remember your father ever talking about the impact when A&M was opened?
Did it have any type of impact on the city, on O'Brien at that time, as far as having a college there?
I don't know.
You know, when I was in high school, Daddy didn't want me to go with Brian Morris, but he didn't mind me going with Aggies.
Isn't that funny?
He was an Aggie, wasn't he?
No, he wasn't.
See, he studied law just on his own.
Oh, I see.
But he didn't mind my having to go with Aggies, but I thought that was funny.
Now kids go with...
You know, the Aggies were older than I was, but he said he just thought they were more responsible.
Mostly I went with Aggies rather than...
I went with one Bryan boy.
High school boy.
That's interesting.
Everybody didn't have steadies then.
You just went with everybody that asked you.
That was fun then.
How was the...
I know it's quite different now when you take someone out on a date.
You had to go over and meet their parents and all that stuff.
Was it pretty conservative back then?
Yes.
And of course, all the Aggies were broke, and none of them had cars, so they were safe.
You walked to the picture show.
Where was the main theater, the picture show?
It was down where it is now.
It's exactly where it was, the palace.
Was that the main...
It was the main one, and then they had the Dixie and the Queen, and I don't even know what shows they have now.
That's how much I know.
Yeah, it's quite different now.
I don't know whether they have those two shows or not, the Queen and the Dixie.

See, they had, the queen used to have good shows, and the palace would have good shows, and the Dixie had, I don't know, maybe things kids went to on Saturday or something, but one of the first, the very first picture I ever saw that was in color was Madame Butterfly.
And, you know, I believe that was hand-colored, if I remember right.
That was years ago.
Years ago.
Before the red card pictures.
When do you remember the first TV you had?
I believe they got TV while we were overseas.
Because I wouldn't have it in the house for years.
I didn't want one.
Why do you still want to be bothered?
I finally...
Well, I remember way back then everyone used to... We just listened to the news mostly.
Well, I remember before they had the TV, a lot of people, the family would sit around the radio and listen to it.
I don't know.
We've always been a pretty active family and we've always been doing something.
Besides we're either reading or studying or painting or doing something else.
So we didn't ever listen to the radio too much.
I listened to the radio during the daytime.
All the time?
No.
What do you do right now?
Oh.
I'm sorry, I forgot.
Well, what I've been doing, was why Jen said this, was I said, in 1973, I went to Blinn College.
I decided I was going to go back to college.
And so I went back, and...
There was another woman that was about 14 years younger than I was, and she was so glad because she says she was the oldest, and now somebody older than her was going.
And so she said she was thrilled to death to have somebody old.
Grandma, you know.
I took English in history.
English in history.
I thought it was going to go on, but my house kept getting dirtier and dirtier.
You know, I needed to get things organized.
So I did that.
Well, then I decided for about three years I was going to start studying family history and get it so that my son and all of them can get their hands on it.
You know, that's why you and I sent you to me.
I've been trying to get these facts in a way that...
some of these young people are beginning to be interested, and unless somebody does it now, it's going to be too late.
Was there any type of, I guess the only type of industry they really had was cotton here then, right?
I believe so, yeah.
That's just about all, as far as I know.
I know that you know what...
It just was a little, just a small town.
I used to, I remember when we went up to Wisconsin, that's where all my family's from.
They used to let us smoke.
I have three brothers and we used to go over in the attic in my grandpa's house and just spend hours up in that attic looking at old stuff.
When my grandfather on my mother's side passed away she brought back a lot of his stuff and it was a will dated 1793.
a will, and it said, you know, to my first son, I bequeathed.
You know, it was really... And, you know, they used to make family trees, too.
They used to have these big old lists, and they'd make up a family tree, you know.
Thy first son, you know, thus named.
And it was really interesting, you know, that's why... What name was that?
Was that Friedli?
Bradfield.
That was my mother's name.
That's British, isn't it?
Yeah, I believe so.
Sounds kind of British.
Yeah.
And Friedli is German.
My grandfather on my dad's side immigrated from Switzerland.
They were real German.
My dad grew up in a little town.
He was born in a cheese factory.
He was?
Yeah.
He grew up around cheese, butter, and milk.
When he went to the University of Wisconsin, he studied dairy science.
That's what brought my parents to Mexico.
A man named Murchison was trying to start a dairy industry down in Monterrey.
Well, not in Monterrey, Mexico.
They lived in Tampico.
And that's why they were down there.
And they lived there for 13 years.
And me and my younger brother were born there while they lived in Monterrey.
And you pretty good speak Spanish.
Yeah, uh-huh.
My son loves Spanish.
Right now, my mom's a Spanish teacher.
She teaches Spanish in high school.
They just left for Europe.
My dad works for Summers Drug Stores, Rexall Drug Stores in San Antonio.
They have a big drug convention in Switzerland.
And that's where all my dad's relatives are.
And he's going to see them for the very first time.
And they just left last Monday, in fact.
They're going to be gone for three weeks.
Well, that's good.
Yeah.
I know a lot about my parents' background up in Wisconsin.
My mom, she's a DAR.
She wanted to, but she never had enough time to join it.
But one of her ancestors was a corporal in the American Revolution and stuff like that.
Well, my husband is from Mississippi.
So while I was making a bunch of family trees for my family, trying to get it,
Also, I'm trying to get to all my nephews and nieces.
I'm trying to just make a little booklet for each of them, and those who want it can preserve it, and that way it won't be, if one house burns up, it won't all be gone.

So I took my husband's family, and I started, I hadn't even looked at his, and I started looking at it, and I found out that two of his ancestors married each other, and both of their fathers were in the...
Revolutionary War.
And I said, hey, you're more elite than I am.
And he says, I'm going to join the D.A.R.
when we get to life.
Because he had a daughter of one of the Revolutionary soldiers and a son.
Some of his relatives had looked it up, but I hadn't bothered with it because until recently, I didn't have time to fool around with it.
What kind of background did your husband come from?
Oh, his father had a grocery store in Mississippi.
And did his father come out here, or did
No, my husband came through in 1928, after he graduated from high school, and he saw A&M.
He did like my grandfather's son.
He saw A&M, he decided to go to A&M.
And so I met him when he was a freshman.
Yeah, all the way from Mississippi, I didn't even know.
To Texas.
And he heard about A&M in Mississippi?
He heard about it, and he decided he'd look it over.
He looked it over.
He came and...
So I don't know what, do they still on the freshman have a, I don't think they do that.
They had a white band they made him wear on the sleeve.
And so I took his white band off the last night he was a freshman.
He was 18 and I was 15, I think.
18, huh?
Oh, wow.
Want me to let your dog in?
He graduated real early.
Want me to go ahead and let your dog in?
No, let it go.
Yeah, I didn't, you know, back then, I didn't even think A&M was that known, that much known about it.
Well, for some reason, he liked it, and he still likes it.
That's great.
You can't say it.
He doesn't want anybody sitting in against him.
We laugh, and anybody comes, he takes them on a tour.
I said they ought to make him pinky down.
Have you ever heard of pinky down?
Yes, I have.
Well, my husband's dad is pinky down.
He takes them all and shows them all the fat pigs.
He's in the mechanical engineering department.
Oh.
But he shows them the engineering things, and he shows them all everything.
Yeah, well, see, I'm...
We're four brothers, and my oldest brother graduated in 72, and my other brother graduated in 74, and I'll graduate next year in 76.
And my other brother's a freshman right now.
And you all went to A&M?
Uh-huh.
My dad went to the University of Wisconsin, but he feels like he's in A&M.
Does he?
Because all his sons have gone to A&M, and they really love it.
Well, that's good.
Your husband's grandparents, were they from around the Mississippi area?
Let me see.
What?
I'll have to find out about his immediate grandparents.
His mother's parents were from the town.
He can't find one on the Mississippi.
And his mother's father was a teacher there.
I think he was a county official at times.
I've forgotten.
I have to go look that up.
I'm going to look up his side after I get through with mine.
But anyway, he has a lot of relatives there.
Do you remember, what's his name, I can't remember his name, this man right here.
W.H.
Minkert.
Minkert.
Did both of his parents die?
Both of them died.
Both of them died?
I think he was about 12.
Oh, really?
And he had a guardian appointed.
This is something that someone told me and now there's nobody to ask.
You know, like maybe Daddy would tell me something and somebody else, he didn't tell them that.
So when I try to verify it, you know, they'll say, no, we didn't talk about that.
I'd ask Daddy questions and different ones would, but maybe we didn't ask him the same questions.
So, but my memory was that he decided he wasn't, I don't know if he thought he was mistreated or what, but anyway, bereft of what his problem was, but he just left.
What kind of a name is that?
M-I-N-K-E-R-T. We can't find anybody past his parents, you see.
They show his parents in the Bible that he was born to these people.
His father's name was W.H.
Manfred II.
What did his father do?
We don't know.
That's all I know about him, see, because they died.
Daddy would have known if we had asked him.
There wasn't anybody else in his family?
We can't find another Nippert in the United States.
And somebody said that they are in Holland.
That we can find them in Holland.
And he spoke Dutch.
He could speak Dutch and English.
And I don't know if he looks Dutch or not.
I can't say that he does.
But he does a little bit.
And she's English.
And she had a private school here about 10 years ago.
Ms. W.H.
Nippert did.
They had in 18...
She had a private school, and a lot of, some of the prominent people sent their children there.
And I asked Daddy why people would send their children to her private school, and he said it was like it is now.
They were getting too tough, you know, and they were afraid the children, there were too many things happening in public schools.
And so she taught it in her home, and she taught it in Masonic Hall, and I guess it's the same one that's here now, in the bottom floor of it, and had about 25 pupils.
And I know, even in my lifetime, some of those people would say that she was a really wonderful teacher.
I'm bragging on it, but anyway, she deserved bragging on it.
And they said that she taught them just wonderful.
And see, she taught her own children, too, and she taught music also.
And I know one time I went with Daddy out to the cemetery, and he used to have the clearest tie.
He said, my mother was the most wonderful woman in the world.
And he never had talked about her much, so she must have been pretty wonderful.
And Daddy said one time that he never had a recess in his life.
He said, I never did get to play because Mother taught school and I had to do all the chores.
He says, the others sloughed off, you know how some mothers are.
And he says, and Daddy was real conscientious, you know.
and he was like this about everything.
If somebody was stuck in the mud, Daddy would go push them out, and everybody was stuck in the mud a long time ago, as you said back then.
Daddy would go push them out, and maybe they'd splatter his clothes when they pushed them out, and he'd come home all splattered up, and Mother would say, yeah, that's just like you.
They wouldn't pay for your clothes to be cleaned.
Well, I had to help them get out of the mud, and he just was always, had somebody he was helping, some family one time, and our Sunday school class decided we were going to help them.
take a family to help.
And we'd help.
Every Christmas, you know, you'd take somebody and you'd take them fruit and everything.

So we got over there and when we went inside, well, I saw this lady and she said, she didn't recognize me at first, I guess, but she says, I don't know what we'd have done if Mr. Minkert hadn't been helping us.
And says he's just kept us alive.
Well, what Daddy would do was he'd try to find work for him.
Was it pretty hard to find anything?
Well, this was a man that was older, and he'd married a younger woman and had this little boy, and his health wasn't too good, but he was a worker.
And so Daddy, if he couldn't find anything for him to do at his yard, he'd come over and have him work in our yard and pay him to work in our yard.
You know, we don't need life.
Maybe we didn't even need him, you know.
But Daddy didn't want to hurt his pride.
That's really great.
And he also, one day he says, you know, little boy's about four or five years old.
He says, I paid him.
He says, that's the first time he ever got paid.
He says, I bet he'll remember that all his life.
He was like that.
He always said, he and Mother, and Mother would fuss, but she did too.
They both always had a...
two, three families.
We weren't that rich, but that was the way to go.
That's nice.
They were unusual people, really.
You said you went to East Pakistan?
Yeah.
For aiming?
My husband was, I guess you'd call a counterpart there to the president of the engineering college there.
He helped him
organized different courses there.
And he wrote a book once over there and donated it to them.
I typed it and he read it eight times.
Didn't get any money for it.
I'm a built-in secretary.
Everybody asks me what I do.
I'm a built-in secretary.
I keep killing myself because I should have taken typing in high school.
You can still take it.
I just got to find the time.
But boy, this year especially, I've had three term papers in my life.
You've got to take it for about six weeks.
That's all I need.
Sometime after you get out.
But it sure would have helped you in college.
Oh, boy.
Well, I might learn this summer.
I'll go to summer camp for the Army.
Yeah.
You can teach yourself if you get a book.
That's what my mom already bought it for me.
If you just take five minutes a day.
Well, anyway, he went over there to help.
A&M had a cooperating program with them.
And they sent somebody to the engineering college, the agricultural college, to a teacher's college.
Let me see what else.

Anyway, we were with the engineering college, and so, you know, we mostly, we didn't try to be a place with many people outside the college, because that kept you busy, because they'd invite you, you know, to the socials.
Yeah, well, how long were you over there?
Four years.
Four years.
And so we got to know pretty good.
Did you like it over there?
Privations, you never heard of them.
I guess you heard of them if you've been in Mexico then.
But they had, see, we went there in 54, and India and Pakistan were divided in 47.
So that was seven years later.
And all these people were like the poor little old Vietnamese.
They were refugees, those in East Pakistan.
Most of them were refugees.
And so there was no industry or anything.
And they had come there with just the clothes on their back.
And they were sweet people.
And the man who was our chief servant, you know everybody has about 10 servants, the man who was our chief servant could speak five languages.
Can you imagine that having to be a servant?
He said, one time I talked to him, he says,
The first time when I knew I had to be a servant, I hated it.
And I thought, a man that brilliant hurt my feelings.
But he could do anything.
I just remembered that they had a yellow fever epidemic that came through here in the late 1890s.
Maybe that was, when you, when I was talking to you, I thought that's what Uncle Willie died with, yellow fever.
Because back then, yes.
Willie Minkert.
Mm-hmm.
Daddy said he was very successful in this grocery store and was young.
But, you know, men branched out early when they had to.
Sure, sure.
And so they would become a man and be on their own when they were real men.
Oh, yeah, nowadays.
Well, it's just people have to prepare longer.
They've got changing times now.
I was just thinking of that.
Yeah, I thought that was what I thought.
Then I thought, well, maybe they didn't have yellow fever, but that was what I thought I remembered.
You died from yellow fever.
I thought it was.
Probably was.
It was some epidemic.
Did you ever know anything about...
them using, uh, navigating on the Brazos River back here?
You probably do, you know?
I can't remember.
Because they used to, uh, at one time they were gonna, you know, make it navigable and everything, and then right after
They decided, they were working on it, then they had the big flood, and the Bradstown was rerouted.
It took a different route.
Well, I see, I don't know, I can't remember.
And it's, you know, and you don't know, you can't see it until you look at aerial photographs of the Bradstown bottom.
